The first symbol of the string is t71.  
Inside the grammar the only non-terminal that can emit t71 directly is 

 NT57 → 't71'.

For a derivation in Chomsky normal form, the left-most terminal of any sentence is obtained by repeatedly following the left child of each binary rule until a single–terminal rule is reached.  
Hence, to have t71 as the first token, some rule in that left-most chain must be of the form

 X → NT57 Y

so that NT57 (and therefore t71) appears first.

Scanning the grammar, the unique rule with NT57 in the left position of a binary production is

 NT101 → NT57 NT49.

Therefore the required left-most chain must reach NT101, after which NT101 produces t71 as its first output symbol.

Now examine the only two possibilities for the start symbol S:

 S → NT86 NT92  
 S → NT112 NT110

• Every derivation beginning with S → NT86 NT92 has its first symbol generated by NT86.  
  NT86, however, expands only as  
 NT86 → NT33 NT96 | NT25 NT32 | NT103 NT37 | 't54'  
  None of NT33, NT25, NT103 nor the literal 't54' can (by any further sequence of left-child expansions) reach NT101, because NT101 never appears on the left side of any binary rule reachable from them. Hence NT86 can never place NT57 first, so it can never produce t71 as the initial token.

• Every derivation beginning with S → NT112 NT110 has its first symbol generated by NT112, and NT112 can expand only as  
 NT112 → 't69' | NT15 NT73  
  The literal 't69' is not t71.  
  If NT112 → NT15 NT73, the first token comes from NT15; yet the only productions for NT15 are  
 NT15 → NT86 NT100 | NT92 NT4 | NT71 NT55  
  As already argued, NT86 cannot reach NT101, and neither NT92 nor NT71 appear in any chain that can reach NT101 either. Thus NT112 also cannot yield t71 as the first token.

Since neither alternative for S can derive a sentence whose first symbol is t71, the given string cannot be generated by the grammar.
